quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  12,1,"Alif Lām Ra. Those are the signs{1}of the Evident Scripture.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  12,2,"Indeed, We have sent it down as an Arabic Recital{1}, that you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>may reason.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  12,3,"We relate to you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>the most beautiful of stories by revealing to you this Recital<a class=""sup""><sup>f </sup></a>, although prior to it you were indeed one of the oblivious.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation
  12,4,"Recall when Joseph said to his father, “O my father, I saw eleven planets and the sun and the moon; I saw them prostrating to me.”"
